The dissociation of SrF₂ in water can be represented as: \[ \mathrm{SrF}_{2}(s) \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{Sr}^{2+}(aq) + 2\mathrm{F}^{-}(aq) \] From this dissociation, we know that if the concentration of \(\mathrm{Sr}^{2+}\) is \(S\), the concentration of \(\mathrm{F}^{-}\) will be \(2S\). The Ksp expression is: \[ K_{sp} = [\mathrm{Sr}^{2+}][\mathrm{F}^{-}]^2 \] Substituting the concentrations in terms of \(S\): \[ K_{sp} = S \cdot (2S)^2 = 4S^3 \] Given \(K_{sp} = 2.45 \times 10^{-9}\), we solve for \(S\): \[ 4S^3 = 2.45 \times 10^{-9} \] \[ S^3 = \frac{2.45 \times 10^{-9}}{4} \] \[ S^3 = 6.125 \times 10^{-10} \] Taking the cube root of both sides: \[ S = \sqrt[3]{6.125 \times 10^{-10}} \] Using logarithms or numerical approximation, we find: \[ S \approx 8.48 \times 10^{-4} \] Verification with the calculated value shows that the Ksp value computed using \(S = 8.48 \times 10^{-4}\) is very close to the given Ksp value, confirming the accuracy of the result. Thus, the solubility of strontium fluoride in water is: \[ \boxed{8.48 \times 10^{-4}} \] M.
